quivalent to k lying in the open interval (6n/7, 7n/8).\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"h₁\",\n        \"step 2\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The length of the interval (6n/7, 7n/8) is n/56.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Its length is 7n/8 - 6n/7 = (49n - 48n)/56 = n/56.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"arithmetic with fractions\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"If an open interval contains exactly one integer, then its length is less than 2, and in this specific situation this forces n/56 < 2.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"An open interval of length at least 2 must contain at least two integers, because any interval of length 2 contains two consecutive integers or more. Since step 3 says there is exactly one integer in the interval, its length must be less than 2. Therefore n/56 < 2.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"pigeonhole principle for integers in intervals\",\n        \"step 3\",\n        \"step 4\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"n < 112.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"From n/56 < 2, multiply both sides by 56 > 0 to get n < 112.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 5\",\n        \"positivity of 56\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"Therefore n ≤ 112.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Since n is an integer and n < 112, it follows that n ≤ 111, hence certainly n ≤ 112.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 6\",\n        \"integrality of n\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"final_answer\": \"n ≤ 112\"\n}\n\nProduce the JSON formalization."
