ime. Also 3 > 0, so the right-hand side of h₀(3) holds, hence 3 ∈ S.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"h₀\",\n        \"direct computation\",\n        \"prime 2\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"If n ∈ S, then n = 3.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"By step 2, n^2 + 2 - 3n must be prime. Using step 1, this number is (n - 1)(n - 2). For n ≥ 4, both factors are at least 2, so the product is composite. For n = 1 or 2, the product is 0, which is not prime. For n = 3, the product is 2, which is prime. Therefore the only possible n is 3.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 1\",\n        \"definition of prime\",\n        \"case analysis on n\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"S = {3}.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Step 3 shows 3 ∈ S, and step 4 shows every element of S must equal 3. Therefore S has exactly one element, namely 3.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 3\",\n        \"step 4\",\n        \"extensionality of finite sets\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"S.card = 1.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"A finite set with exactly one element has cardinality 1.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 5\",\n        \"finite set cardinality\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"final_answer\": \"1\"\n}\n\nProduce the JSON formalization."
